    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>San Francisco</placeName>
                <date><add>?</add> 19. 1857</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">My Dear friend:—</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Yours of the <date>4th of Nov.</date> &amp; enclosed
                commu-<lb/>nication from <persName>Dr. Finskel</persName>, has been duly
                re-<lb/>ceived. I have, in accordance with your request,<lb/> presented
                    <persName>Dr. F's</persName> letter &amp; likewise your own<lb/> to the
                President of the Congregation “Emanu_El,” by<lb/> whom the proper attention was paid
                to it. The<lb/> President, <persName>Mr. L. Tichener</persName>, on behalf of
                the<lb/> congregation requests me to return many<lb/> thanks to you for your trouble
                in the endeavor<lb/> of procuring a minister. I have to ask<lb/> your pardon in
                delaying to answer your letter,<lb/> the cause of which is that I have been
                un-<lb/>usually busy.—The Congregation has received<lb/> now two applications_one
                from <persName>Dr. Hoelzel</persName><lb/> now at <placeName>Australia</placeName>,
                the other from a <persName>Rev Cohn</persName><lb/> now at
                        <placeName><sic>Albani</sic></placeName>; as no general meeting has<lb/> of
                late occurred, no action had been<lb/> taken upon these applications. According
                to<lb/> the occidents &amp; statements by the Heb. Journal<lb/> (the Chronicle_I
                believe) shown to me, &amp; various<lb/> other proofs, I conclude that <persName>Dr.
                    H.</persName> must be a<lb/> competent and suitable minister of <persName>Rev.
                    Cohn</persName> I<lb/> have nothing heard, but undoubtedly you are<lb/>
                acquainted with that gentleman.</p>
            <p><persName>Mr. H. Bien's</persName> term of office expires in about</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>five weeks. At the regular meeting that was<lb/> some time since held for the purpose
                of electing<lb/> a Minister <persName>Mr. Bien</persName> has not handed in any<lb/>
                application for that office.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Another Jewish Journal called the “Gleaner”<lb/> under the
                editorship of <persName>Dr. Julias Eckman</persName><lb/> has last
                    <date>Friday</date> made its appearance.—<lb/> I will send you a copy—Thus
                making five Hebrew sheets in <hi rend="underline">this city</hi>.</p>
            <p>I have of late not given to you any news,<lb/> thinking it unnecessary, as we
                have<lb/> now Jewish papers published here, &amp; such<lb/> news, that are of any
                importance, you<lb/> can therefore extract from them. But should<lb/> you prefer, to
                have them few news occur-<lb/>-ring here communicated by myself,<lb/> I will do the
                same with pleasure.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am anxiously awaiting the “advocate,”<lb/> &amp; then I hope to
                procure a good number<lb/> of subscribers for it</p>
            <p>In compliance with your wish, I return<lb/> you enclosed <persName>Dr.
                    Frankel's</persName> Letter.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">with many wishes for Your Prosperity</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I remain</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">Cauffman H. M<add>?</add></persName>
            </p>
        </body>
